WEBVTT

00:01.803 --> 00:26.646
We were talking about the second method course 
that we have and I was telling you that in that one we

00:01.803 --> 00:26.646
cover about five, six different topics and one is 
the land use transportation methods and it's a

00:01.803 --> 00:26.646
little perhaps mathematical and theoretical but 
the intention is that to cover the concepts which

00:26.626 --> 00:31.314
would be helpful for planners to understand the 
urban and especially the regional area. By

00:31.454 --> 00:34.058
regional, I mean like Dallas-Fort Worth region. I 
don't mean big regions like Texas, etc. And I found

00:37.464 --> 00:45.938
out that that is very much helpful for planners to 
go through that exposition to understand all

00:37.464 --> 00:45.938
those theories. And then another topic of 
importance is evaluation we go through the

00:52.090 --> 01:09.306
basically cost benefit type of things and we have 
exercises to do and in fact the planning related

00:52.090 --> 01:09.306
exercise to go through I think that's very 
important for them to basically to be exposed to

01:09.286 --> 01:18.326
Then we have population and employment 
projection methods, which I think any planner

01:09.286 --> 01:18.326
should be able to do rough calculation of the 
projection of what's going to happen in the

01:09.286 --> 01:18.326
future. Do you use cohort? The cohort survival and 
also the trend analysis of linear trend, curve

01:21.373 --> 01:27.065
linear trends, etc. Their formulation, how to do 
it. In fact, there is an assignment for them to do

01:28.709 --> 01:32.857
that, to do these type of things. Do they do it by 
hand, or do they use a computer program? No, in this

01:37.305 --> 01:39.089
course, no computer. Computer is mostly in the 
statistics course, and they do basically... I

01:43.317 --> 01:49.268
have cut all the proofs, et cetera, in the 
statistics course, as basically to... I'm

01:49.288 --> 01:50.751
presenting them where... the conceptual things 
that in my mind they need to know but there are five

01:51.372 --> 02:15.304
major computer assignments that they put 
together data and basically starting from the

01:51.372 --> 02:15.304
simplest one they do one by one and get to the 
regression assignment which is the most complex

01:51.372 --> 02:15.304
one and then we repeat the regression assignment 
also in the second method course as just the review

02:15.284 --> 02:44.464
just again because of my own view that I think 
regression is the most applied and close to

02:15.284 --> 02:44.464
planning and can be applied and they put together 
some planning related one in the second course and

02:15.284 --> 02:44.464
basically do that here they learn both a major 
statistical package computer package both

02:15.284 --> 02:44.464
courses I mean and also they go and apply that so 
hopefully they're gonna become efficient with

02:15.284 --> 02:44.464
that but then rest of the course all the 
assignments are manual like that population

02:45.035 --> 03:14.991
projection one is a manual one and then the 
evaluation one which is a major development case

02:45.035 --> 03:14.991
in the downtown and they're going to evaluate to 
see if does it work to make to basically build it it

02:45.035 --> 03:14.991
is for cities like a parking structure or 
something a feasibility study basically to see is

02:45.035 --> 03:14.991
it beneficial for them to they have a piece of land 
and they're gonna see that if it is good for them to

02:45.035 --> 03:14.991
build a big parking structure public parking or 
would be better for them to sell to someone else to

03:14.971 --> 03:30.887
make an office building or whatever something 
like that but there's so many issues involved like

03:14.971 --> 03:30.887
transportation they have a rail system coming and 
the benefit of putting a parking here versus

03:14.971 --> 03:30.887
reducing the rail, transit riders, etc. Then we 
have overview of shift and share and input output,

03:34.112 --> 03:44.707
those type of regional economic analysis that I 
thought the concepts is necessary for them. We

03:45.428 --> 03:56.183
have review of linear programming in a sense that 
linear programming in some senses are exactly

03:45.428 --> 03:56.183
planning because you want to maximize the 
benefits to the society under given such

03:56.163 --> 04:00.931
constants, and that is basically the definition 
of planning. And then you have a methodology that

04:01.312 --> 04:04.016
basically does that. Again, we don't want to make 
them applied linear programmers or something. We

04:08.985 --> 04:15.977
just want them to know that there is such a concept 
very similar to planning and a basic mathematical

04:08.985 --> 04:15.977
concept that can be done. There are a bunch of these 
type of small methods. I have written a small

04:19.858 --> 04:23.742
paper, which unfortunately I haven't been able to 
publish that. We're basically going through my

04:23.762 --> 04:28.747
philosophy of the method courses for planning. If 
you are interested, I can provide you with a copy.

04:31.650 --> 04:33.332
Yeah, I'd like that very much. I used to teach the 
course in methods and techniques at A&M.

04:40.259 --> 04:43.062
So here is another architect teaching. It was a 
course that I came to enjoy, but I was backed into it

04:43.598 --> 04:52.792
because no one else wanted to teach it. And so I had 
to become familiar with demographic forecasting

04:54.214 --> 05:03.989
and different economic-based theories and 
whatnot. And then, of course, we got computers in

05:04.009 --> 05:08.656
our department. Everybody thought that we should 
get computerized in that course. which I was

05:13.147 --> 05:39.238
reluctant to do because I felt that the students 
should know how to do this by hand, and that

05:13.147 --> 05:39.238
particularly with the cohort survival 
technique, that they might lose one of the

05:13.147 --> 05:39.238
essential attributes of the technique in not 
cranking in changes in migration rates by cohort

05:39.674 --> 05:57.091
or survival rates or whatever, and that they would 
just simply punch a button and the computer would

05:39.674 --> 05:57.091
assume everything would stay the same and it would 
grind out numbers, which is exactly what happened

05:39.674 --> 05:57.091
after I was almost forced to go to computer on it by 
outside pressures in the department. So it

05:58.452 --> 06:09.563
happened, and I predicted it would, and I think 
that it was a mistake to do that. the computers to be

06:09.661 --> 06:28.868
used at all, I think it should be at the end of the 
semester where it's a hands-on sort of thing and

06:09.661 --> 06:28.868
the students are required to make changes in 
migration rights and birth and death rates and so

06:09.661 --> 06:28.868
forth. cohort and by time increment. You know, I 
don't use computer in that course exactly for,

06:33.780 --> 06:50.772
partly for that reason and partly because up to now 
there is no good packages available to do that, to

06:33.780 --> 06:50.772
do gravity model, to do land use model, etc. And 
even if become available, I guess that would be

06:51.308 --> 06:57.927
another course that, OK, we covered the theory. 
Now let us go and do applied in the computer.

07:02.952 --> 07:06.216
Personally, I don't want to spend time of learning 
those computer things. Every day, they are

07:06.396 --> 07:08.539
changing all these packages. But I guess if ever I 
was forced to do the same way, I'd have to do

07:09.140 --> 07:14.947
something about it. I think for us as the planners, 
it's more important to understand the concepts.

07:18.971 --> 07:23.737
And if we really need to use it, we can always go 
ahead and learn the packages. And especially that

07:23.857 --> 07:29.124
nowadays, they try to put the packages in a way that 
one can learn by himself. So they can go and learn it

07:29.144 --> 07:31.727
and apply it. Taking a look at the future of 
planning education in Texas, do you see any

07:33.310 --> 07:55.729
changes in the whole system of having three

07:33.310 --> 07:55.729
certified programs?

07:55.749 --> 08:03.115
You know, I know that we have three programs which 
may look a little small for such a big state. But on

08:03.635 --> 08:10.484
the other hand, I believe that none of the schools 
has been too big to justify any other program. As

08:10.524 --> 08:15.191
far as I know, all three programs have had only a 
handful of students. Am I right? I think so. Well,

08:16.893 --> 08:23.281
we usually have, at any one time, around 65 to 70 
enrolled. In master program or? Well, in all three

08:24.924 --> 08:26.966
degree programs. We have the Master of Science in 
Land Development, the MUP, and the PhD. But if you

08:33.942 --> 08:44.198
put the PhD separate, and perhaps in the land 
development a little bit separate, you are going

08:33.942 --> 08:44.198
to have about 40, am I right? 40 is not, I mean, 40 you 
and perhaps about 30, 40... If we stay with 40 that

08:51.340 --> 08:56.626
we are now, it would be 120. And I remember coming 
from Los Angeles area, in Los Angeles alone, there

08:58.588 --> 09:06.096
were three, four planning programs. Each one of 
them, at least UCLA and USC, I believe, had about

09:07.477 --> 09:14.465
50, 60 each. And then there was Cal Poly program 
that had 150 students or something. Pomona one.

09:22.112 --> 09:31.824
And then there was that private school I forgot 
which the name of the program wasn't directly

09:22.112 --> 09:31.824
planning, it was something like public 
administration. Pepperdine? Pepperdine. They

09:33.446 --> 09:34.948
had some students there too. So one metropolitan 
area almost having twice of all our students. So in

09:41.076 --> 09:45.782
some sense I don't think that we need more schools, 
at least for now. But on the other hand, I believe

09:45.998 --> 09:59.674
that this growth which happened in Texas happened 
so fast that so many of the communities couldn't

09:45.998 --> 09:59.674
realize that they needed planners to handle that. 
But now that the wave is gone and they have seen how

10:00.294 --> 10:07.683
much mistakes they have done, hopefully they 
realize that they have done mistakes. Some of them

10:07.883 --> 10:11.247
I'm sure they won't realize. Some of them are 
realizing now and they are starting to hire or to

10:11.918 --> 10:19.691
feel that gradually they need to have such staff 
there. So I feel that gradually, very slowly, the

10:19.711 --> 10:29.927
demand for planners is going to increase a little 
bit, at least in the public sector, especially in

10:19.711 --> 10:29.927
cities and counties, et cetera. if that trend is 
correct then perhaps we're going to have a little

10:30.211 --> 10:50.532
bit more demand but that doesn't to me that doesn't 
mean that we're going to have 100 students each or

10:30.211 --> 10:50.532
something means that we're going to move from 40 to 
50 because we are talking about stable type of

10:30.211 --> 10:50.532
situations but in regard to what area we'll need to 
cover for those things. Of course, one area is just

10:54.582 --> 11:13.374
dealing with the growth and managing the urban 
areas, because it is traditional in Texas that so

10:54.582 --> 11:13.374
many areas have just used to manage the urban areas 
without planning, or even without zoning, as the

10:54.582 --> 11:13.374
case of Houston, etc. And gradually, I think, 
these things would, the wave has started, of

11:16.634 --> 11:23.601
course, years ago to come from west and east to 
here. And if we consider that trend, we're going to

11:24.782 --> 11:33.751
see that more cities are going to have formal 
planning organizations or counties. So there is a

11:34.052 --> 11:36.354
need in that side to be fulfilled. I think we have a 
mission to teach actual practice of planning in

11:36.374 --> 11:45.223
terms of physical planning, that they go and do it. 
On the other hand, there are all the new areas of

11:45.710 --> 11:56.322
planning, which has been, I don't know, the output 
of, say, 60s and 70s. And perhaps in some regions,

11:56.862 --> 12:01.347
it's starting to come down and semi-die off. Some 
of those ways are going to come here, like social

12:01.367 --> 12:08.595
planning a little bit, or I don't know, other 
health planning. other discussions which may not

12:08.795 --> 12:37.789
be directly a core area of planning or physical 
planning or so and those I think being already

12:08.795 --> 12:37.789
discovered by different communities and 
organizations even private sector one as we were

12:08.795 --> 12:37.789
talking real estate etc I think there is also 
demand there that we got to try to fulfill those so

12:08.795 --> 12:37.789
overall the way I see planning here and I think that 
we should gear up to train people for both of those,

12:38.039 --> 12:52.661
both the public side, which is the actual physical 
planning side, but also the other social and art

12:38.039 --> 12:52.661
things.

12:52.681 --> 13:01.515
We have one student that graduated with a clear 
idea of going into institutional planning.

13:02.204 --> 13:04.567
I didn't quite know what he meant by that. I don't 
know what you're talking about. But what he wanted

13:08.511 --> 13:21.045
to do was actually restructure organizations

13:08.511 --> 13:21.045
and to look at them from an effectiveness point of 
view. And he started out in the New Orleans school

13:21.806 --> 13:26.311
district. So there are all sorts of little niches 
that people can move into. The question that has

13:32.596 --> 13:54.540
come up with Paul that perhaps the three 
accredited schools can't teach every specialty

13:32.596 --> 13:54.540
and that maybe we ought to get together and 
identify what the needs of Texas are. And then

13:55.141 --> 13:56.382
separate the area. And then who has what kinds of 
current capabilities and then draw some

14:01.823 --> 14:04.325
conclusions from that. And we already have a 
cooperative agreement with the University of

14:05.646 --> 14:13.373
Texas at Austin. And that, frankly, is on paper 
only. It doesn't seem to be functioning very well.

14:21.100 --> 14:22.261
Which is what? Pardon? Which is what? That a 
student can take a course at the University of

14:23.863 --> 14:29.468
Texas If it is similar to what offered at A&M, they 
can take it, for example, during the summertime if

14:29.785 --> 14:36.575
they are in an internship there. And we can include 
it in their degree program for credit at A&M, which

14:36.835 --> 14:44.907
seems only logical. But logic does not prevail in 
academia. Yeah, especially by the way of funding.

14:52.773 --> 14:57.058
I don't know how is your funding system, but I 
believe it would be very similar to ours.

14:57.078 --> 15:00.261
Eventually, we are one type of system, I think. If 
you are going to create ours, you've got to

15:00.281 --> 15:08.110
naturally try to keep all the created ours for 
yourself, and that would create the problem.

15:08.130 --> 15:09.872
Sure. So it's a problem. We ran into all sorts of red 
tape with this one particular student. Not all of

15:18.655 --> 15:33.235
it because of the institutional arrangements, 
some of it was because of the enthusiasm of the

15:18.655 --> 15:33.235
student in moving ahead of the ability of the 
organizational structure to handle it. But these

15:33.255 --> 15:38.983
sorts of things can be worked out, it seems to me. 
And not that I think that there's an advantage of

15:39.243 --> 15:45.912
having multiple schools and planning. And I also 
think that UT Arlington is geographically

15:46.516 --> 15:54.208
situated the best of any of them. Yeah, because the 
other one is in Austin, and there's nothing in

15:54.228 --> 15:58.534
Houston. You are the closest one to Houston. Well, 
Texas Southern. But they are not accurate. Do they

16:06.146 --> 16:08.049
have a planning program? Essentially no longer.

16:13.017 --> 16:15.240
That, it's... predominantly Negro college, and 
John Shanahan taught there for a while, but he's no

16:15.980 --> 16:27.056
longer with them.

16:27.196 --> 16:32.444
Are there any thoughts that you want to include 
that we haven't already touched on? Not really at

16:32.825 --> 16:35.689
this moment. Just come to my mind later. Okay, 
well, you'll be getting a transcript of this

16:38.052 --> 16:41.177
whenever It's completed. Sure. And then you can go 
over it again and make any notations you wish.

