16:55.002 --> 16:58.267
This is June 19, 1987. We are in the office of Dr. 
Joel Goldstein at the University of Texas in

16:58.848 --> 17:04.296
Arlington. Joel, let's begin with your 
background, your education, your first

17:05.137 --> 17:21.480
professional work, and then how it came that you 
landed at Arlington. Let's go back in history. I

17:23.222 --> 17:28.630
was an undergraduate to a bachelor's degree in 
architecture from the University of

17:23.222 --> 17:28.630
Pennsylvania in Philadelphia. and was an 
assistant for a number of planning professors and

17:29.740 --> 17:39.730
courses, a work assistant as an undergraduate. 
Got interested in planning, took planning

17:39.750 --> 17:49.360
courses, had joint studios with Paul Davidoff and 
Ian McCarr and a bunch of others. Was Myerson there

17:49.480 --> 17:50.601
then? Yes. Everybody was there. Dykman, Wheaton. 
Yes. The golden era. Right. The golden era. I got

17:59.710 --> 18:05.438
interested in planning and knew that I wasn't 
going to... What was the date you got your

17:59.710 --> 18:05.438
architecture degree? June 1963. And it was... I 
knew that I wasn't going to just be an architect

18:10.886 --> 18:15.613
with my professional planning degree. I was going 
to get a professional planning degree someday or

18:15.633 --> 18:18.637
other. And I ended up working and practicing and 
getting licensed in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania

18:19.959 --> 18:28.671
first. I'm taking the licensing exam for New 
Jersey, no reciprocity across the river. I take

18:35.087 --> 18:36.449
the exam all over again. I'm licensed in New Jersey 
as an architect, and I look for graduate schools.

18:42.177 --> 18:44.701
It was after about six years of practice in 
Philadelphia.

18:49.208 --> 18:51.070
Okay. And ended up looking at schools and ended up 
getting a master's in urban design at Washington

18:54.740 --> 19:20.486
University in St. Louis, spending about a year 
there on campus, and then went for a couple of years

18:54.740 --> 19:20.486
to Tulsa, Oklahoma to run a community design 
center in a black neighborhood in a low-income

18:54.740 --> 19:20.486
Indian neighborhood in Tulsa for a couple of 
years. What year was that? That was 1969-70.

19:26.600 --> 19:39.114
And during that time, I lived in Tulsa, worked at 
the design center, and commuted to Stillwater

19:26.600 --> 19:39.114
three days a week for classes, other classes I was 
responsible for as a faculty member. And worked in

19:40.836 --> 19:52.590
Citizens Action there, and then more or less had a 
better offer in Detroit and went on the faculty of

19:40.836 --> 19:52.590
the University of Detroit. as an associate 
professor, jumping rank from assistant to

19:52.570 --> 19:57.055
associate. And at the same time, worked in the 
profession as second in charge of architectural

19:58.137 --> 20:13.815
design and chief planner for Giffles Associates 
in Detroit, the third largest AE firm in the world.

20:15.257 --> 20:21.244
Flew all around the country doing projects while I 
was on the faculty. at the University of Detroit,

20:22.051 --> 20:26.056
teaching planning, urban design, and 
architecture. Sounds like a good combination.

20:29.200 --> 20:35.227
Yeah, it was for a couple of years, and then I took my 
PhD while I was doing all of that. And ended up,

20:37.210 --> 20:50.286
about the five years I was in Detroit, the last 
three years, not teaching at University of

20:37.210 --> 20:50.286
Detroit, but just doing my PhD in Giffles 
Associates. and got my PhD at Michigan State

20:51.768 --> 21:11.339
University, East Lansing, in urban and regional 
planning with cognate areas in social psychology

20:51.768 --> 21:11.339
and political science, social change, studying 
psychology and psychometric, psychological

20:51.768 --> 21:11.339
statistics. Strange combination. So you moved 
away from physical design. Totally into this

21:16.706 --> 21:20.910
social planning. Then I

21:20.930 --> 21:30.160
was offered the job here to come in as the first 
director of the planning program in the School of

21:20.930 --> 21:30.160
Architecture. Probably in 1975,

21:31.061 --> 21:42.193
fall of 1975, as their first director of the 
planning program. the new planning program here

21:42.393 --> 21:45.738
at UT Arlington. That's when we met. Right.

21:50.185 --> 22:12.197
And one thing, as an inexperienced planning 
professor

21:50.185 --> 22:12.197
at this school, inexperienced with Texas, I began 
to learn and practice in my spare time when I wasn't

21:50.185 --> 22:12.197
involved with university duties.

22:13.730 --> 22:20.424
Dallas-Fort Worth and big projects around the 
country.

22:20.444 --> 22:28.640
Taking a look at the program here, what would you 
say are its strong points and its weak points?

22:29.823 --> 22:31.286
Strong ones first. Definite strong points is its 
balanced balanced emphasis towards development

22:35.937 --> 22:46.516
and

22:35.937 --> 22:46.516
cities. In other words, the social aspects, the 
residents, are not seen as black hats or white

22:54.500 --> 22:56.442
hats. The developers are not seen as black hats or 
white hats. Both sides seem to be taught by the

22:59.886 --> 23:04.672
faculty as being equally as important. The 
balance is there. Number two, I think that the

23:07.375 --> 23:22.752
strong point is that as a commuting school, the 
only one in the region that we know of, by region I

23:07.375 --> 23:22.752
mean broad, let's say six, seven, eight state 
regions, where are primarily a commuting school,

23:24.200 --> 23:29.287
a night program. And that's a strength because in 
the tight times of planning jobs in this almost 12

23:30.709 --> 23:48.452
years that I've been here, it has given students an 
opportunity to enroll in a planning program, get

23:30.709 --> 23:48.452
their first job while a student, and graduate with 
two or three years experience by the time they

23:49.512 --> 23:55.761
finish their coursework and they've graduated. 
So they're already working in their job when they

23:56.542 --> 23:59.126
graduate. Or they're moving to their second job 
with two or three years experience. So I think

24:04.193 --> 24:05.315
that's very strong. Yeah, it has benefits in the 
classroom, too. Yes, it does. There's lots of war

24:08.660 --> 24:10.963
stories that get told. And there's a lot of 
networking that the students do between each

24:12.547 --> 24:18.354
other in the classroom. The disadvantages are the 
same thing. Those commuting students are tired

24:20.637 --> 24:23.241
from having worked all day. They come in the 
classroom at night, 7 o'clock at night. Many of

24:26.705 --> 24:32.673
them can't keep their head up because they've been 
studying hard the nights before in preparation

24:26.705 --> 24:32.673
for classwork. And you can't go as late as you'd 
like. What about the faculty? Faculty are sleepy,

24:39.477 --> 24:40.639
too. Demands on the faculty. Faculty, if you teach 
two nights a week, which is our typical teaching

24:42.361 --> 24:58.079
load, until 10.30 at night, from 7 to 10.30, the 
pressures, the social pressures of the job are to

24:42.361 --> 24:58.079
be in your office all during the day. And if you're 
not in in the morning, the other faculty kind of

24:58.961 --> 25:01.604
wander. So there's a lot of pressure, so you end up 
with a lot of unproductive time because you're so

25:05.197 --> 25:08.001
physically tired. It is not the ideal academic 
situation. It's great for students. It's been

25:14.309 --> 25:15.470
great for students. The way the economy is, it's 
been bad for faculty. In

25:18.414 --> 25:33.634
terms of the substance of the curriculum here in 
your Master of City and Regional Planning degree,

25:34.677 --> 25:42.026
How do you feel that this compares with other 
master's degrees in planning around the

25:34.677 --> 25:42.026
countryside?

25:45.490 --> 26:00.448
I would say that a number of schools we've heard 
about, your side, not with checking, they have

25:45.490 --> 26:00.448
their actual, any kind of, running any actual 
testing of their graduates or anything. appears

26:01.154 --> 26:05.140
many of them are just social welfare planning 
oriented programs. Some of the others are

26:06.301 --> 26:15.475
strictly public agency training kinds of 
programs as a result of accreditation

26:06.301 --> 26:15.475
guidelines. I think where we kind of have 
succeeded over the years is that we're trying to

26:15.495 --> 26:24.107
train people to go into real estate and land 
development jobs as well as consulting jobs in

26:24.644 --> 26:34.435
addition to the public sector traditional 
planning jobs. And because of the job market the

26:35.496 --> 26:40.682
way it is in the metro area, the job opportunities 
have existed. And we have a number of students that

26:41.223 --> 26:47.230
have entered our program and worked for major 
developers, major national developers.

26:47.770 --> 26:50.854
Dallas-Fort Worth has the advantage of having 
some the most major development companies in the

26:51.323 --> 26:57.110
United States and Canada here. So it's been a 
confluence of real estate and land development

26:57.130 --> 27:02.317
dollars for the United States. They've spilled in 
here from Germany, from Canada, bounce in Dallas,

27:02.377 --> 27:10.667
Fort Worth, and then spill over into Houston, 
