I would say the curriculum has been just worked on 
over the past two or three years in creating a new

28:23.039 --> 28:33.397
program that was just initiated about a year ago. I 
don't think that any fault will be found in the new

28:33.417 --> 28:40.428
program by the accreditation team. I think there 
may be some structural changes according to the

28:41.170 --> 28:49.063
way the planning program has been administered in 
to the Institute of Urban Studies that go

28:49.499 --> 29:02.497
negatively to the guidelines for accreditation. 
Well then it might help the program quite a bit by

29:02.517 --> 29:10.327
having the outside comments.

29:10.347 --> 29:11.008
I believe so. Politically I don't really wish to 
elaborate on that. Okay, we'll go on to another

29:17.116 --> 29:19.219
topic. Regarding the future of Texas and 
particularly planning for the future in Texas, do

29:20.245 --> 29:41.967
you see any changes in the offing in regard to 
planning education to meet any possible changes?

29:41.987 --> 29:48.514
I think the most critical thing today is learning 
to effectively infiltrate citizens groups to

29:50.013 --> 29:58.282
create behavioral change, that planning is being 
stopped by residents. Any kind of change is being

29:58.422 --> 30:01.745
affected. City budgets are being affected by 
residents. The not in my backyard syndrome is

30:05.689 --> 30:16.721
rampant with all the displacees that have come 
here to make their fortunes, to live in the

30:05.689 --> 30:16.721
Dallas-Fort Worth area and into Texas. People are 
settling in. And I think that it's almost going to

30:19.308 --> 30:41.060
have to be for the same kind of citizens' action 
kinds of activities by planners into the 90s, the

30:19.308 --> 30:41.060
1990s, that are going to be very similar to the 60s 
of the years of social planning, social welfare

30:19.308 --> 30:41.060
planning, for opposite reasons. A rebirth of 
advocacy planning? Not advocacy, but let's say

30:44.685 --> 30:48.471
reverse advocacy planning. in favor of 
pro-development in order for people to be able to

30:48.755 --> 30:55.164
get through the economic conditions of the times. 
In other words, I see fiscal stress due to a federal

30:55.845 --> 31:05.059
deficit, budget deficit, and people having less 
and less discretionary income. As a result of

31:05.620 --> 31:18.238
that, they can very well benefit by planning, by 
having sound fiscal planning that is through

31:05.620 --> 31:18.238
effective pro-development postures being to 
their ultimate advantage, that planning on the

31:19.383 --> 31:42.353
basis of what people want for them, they may not, 
they need to be led to what they should have through

31:19.383 --> 31:42.353
professionalism, more of an elitist attitude, 
but yet through a participatory mode. It's

31:43.582 --> 31:44.403
interesting. Paul Geisel, in answer to that 
question, felt that planning had resurrected its

31:44.884 --> 32:06.609
good name, which came to me as a surprise because I 
think that in our area of Texas and College Station

31:44.884 --> 32:06.609
and East Central Texas, planning is still a dirty 
word. But he felt that in the Metroplex area, that

32:10.818 --> 32:31.105
because of citizen participation and citizen 
planning of neighborhoods, that planning had

32:10.818 --> 32:31.105
again become quite a

32:10.818 --> 32:31.105
positive force and had achieved a new degree of 
respect.

32:33.734 --> 32:53.513
I think there's a respect there, but I think the 
respect is there on the part of the local elected

32:33.734 --> 32:53.513
officials who are running all the land use 
decision-making, because they can hide behind it

32:33.734 --> 32:53.513
effectively from a legal perspective and make 
their own self-interest decisions. So I think

32:55.315 --> 33:02.222
that's where planning may be considered 
resurrected in the minds of the elected

32:55.315 --> 33:02.222
officials. As far as actual planning goes, I think 
not. I think that they're clearly doing

33:07.502 --> 33:16.774
themselves in with exclusionary planning and 
exclusionary zoning without planning. Without

33:18.556 --> 33:28.549
planning, yes, which is conceptually an 
unacceptable procedure. Absolutely. they

33:30.738 --> 33:35.347
certainly wouldn't be able to get away with that in 
Oregon, where planning has mattered. Or

33:35.367 --> 33:44.625
Michigan, or Wisconsin, or Florida, 
Pennsylvania, which isn't as strong as other

33:35.367 --> 33:44.625
states, and on and on, Tennessee.

33:47.731 --> 33:50.316
Planning has been very undeveloped in Texas. And 
you can see it and you can feel it when you operate in

33:50.532 --> 33:54.517
the arena of planning. It's clear. It's been 
undeveloped. There's been no traditional

33:57.341 --> 34:03.288
planning that I can put my finger on except for Fort 
Worth, Texas. Fort Worth has had the tradition

34:03.869 --> 34:18.447
because it's been almost like a city of beautiful 
activity by the elite who have been dilettantes in

34:03.869 --> 34:18.447
the planning since the 54 Victor Gruen plant and 
going back even earlier than that. I haven't

34:19.608 --> 34:23.072
written about Fort Worth yet, but I have written 
about El Paso. And El Paso's planning program got

34:23.412 --> 34:26.616
started in 1919. And they've been doing it ever 
since. In fact, there's a question about whether

34:30.481 --> 34:41.133
or not their city council was the first in the 
country to adopt a comprehensive plan that was

34:30.481 --> 34:41.133
professionally formulated. One usually thinks 
that this happened in 1925 in, was it Cincinnati? I

34:49.392 --> 34:52.116
think it was Cincinnati. With Bettman? Yes, with 
Bettman and others. And the question I'm going to

34:56.302 --> 35:05.857
have to research is the exact date on which all city 
councils took action. Because it might be that El

35:05.877 --> 35:11.485
Paso, we might have to rewrite history. When I 
first began here in 1975, the dean was Dean Hal Box,

35:13.338 --> 35:27.112
who was an architect and was in practice in Dallas 
with the two others. Architectural.

35:28.553 --> 35:29.734
Architectural practice. And Hal Box was dean for 
approximately a year during my time to a year and a

35:39.393 --> 35:49.897
half, I forget exactly which, but sometime either 
fall of 76 or spring of 77 he left to become dean of UT

35:39.393 --> 35:49.897
Austin. At that time an acting dean, or interim 
dean, was George Wright, for about a year or two,

35:56.251 --> 36:03.486
and they had a search, and the university selected 
George Wright to be the new dean. George Wright

36:03.946 --> 36:05.009
stayed there. Another architect? Another 
architect from Albuquerque. They'd been in an

36:09.117 --> 36:12.724
unsuccessful practice in Albuquerque. And he had 
been an assistant to Hal Box, and that's how he

36:13.447 --> 36:20.414
basically got it. Older man, the oldest person on 
the faculty just about, so therefore you must know

36:20.695 --> 36:28.503
something because he's of age. And

36:29.864 --> 36:42.998
what then happened was that planning was 
considered a program with a shared budget with a

36:43.585 --> 36:52.454
landscape architecture program, architecture 
and interior design. The numbers were

36:54.096 --> 37:03.806
misbalanced and all of the undergraduates 
selecting a major were advised by architecture

36:54.096 --> 37:03.806
professors. Sounds like A&M. So the architecture 
professors steered, in my opinion, steered

37:11.497 --> 37:30.077
students into architecture, the bulk was in 
architecture, a very few in number or interior

37:11.497 --> 37:30.077
design, and planning got, did not get their share 
in the undergraduate emphasis. As far as the

37:30.938 --> 37:39.867
graduate program went, we were left alone, but we 
shared budgets with architecture and planning,

37:30.938 --> 37:39.867
graduate. Our first students were... Is that 
still the situation? No, let me give you the

37:44.118 --> 37:45.741
history. Upon applying for accreditation and 
working with it, the former dean, Dean Wright,

37:47.043 --> 38:01.144
gave separate budgeting power and autonomy of 
program to the planning program. And we obtained

38:02.346 --> 38:09.617
our accreditation, I believe, in 77 or 78, 
remarkably quick. because of their support. And

38:15.267 --> 38:38.743
we had four years within the School of 
Architecture, and during that time, the planning

38:15.267 --> 38:38.743
faculty, Gene Brooks and a fellow named Barry 
Rubin, who was a graduate of the University of

38:15.267 --> 38:38.743
Wisconsin, and some graduate students, of ours 
made a political move to get planning out of the

38:39.888 --> 39:00.467
School of Architecture and successfully moved it 
out of architecture, succeeded in doing so, and

38:39.888 --> 39:00.467
moved it into the graduate school. Jean Brooks 
stayed behind in the School of Architecture as a

39:01.168 --> 39:06.773
teacher of undergraduate urban design Barry 
Rubin got a distaste for the university and left to

39:07.580 --> 39:16.210
go to the University of Indiana to teach planning.

39:20.514 --> 39:36.152
So we were under the graduate dean as an 
interdisciplinary program for two years with a

39:20.514 --> 39:36.152
sociologist for a department chairman. who had 
been appointed by new disciplinary planning

39:37.448 --> 39:41.313
faculty. Who was that? That was Lee Taylor, 
L-E-E-T-A-Y-L-O-R.

39:42.314 --> 40:06.426
Lee Taylor's interest was Newtowns as a 
sociologist, and at the end of two years,

39:42.314 --> 40:06.426
we clearly did not have faculty representation on 
campus on any committees, faculty senate, and all

40:07.317 --> 40:07.958
that. And the dean of the graduate school had us as 
the only academic unit under his tutelage. So he

40:13.582 --> 40:14.383
didn't want us. So we were asked to recommend a 
place on campus. Vice President for Academic

40:20.768 --> 40:32.798
Affairs went to our faculty, and we agreed with his 
recommendation to come into the Institute of

40:20.768 --> 40:32.798
Urban Studies, which we are now. We came in as a 
full-fledged department. with accreditation.

40:39.391 --> 40:42.055
We had an accreditation team visit within two 
years. At that time, which was about six years

40:42.696 --> 40:54.513
thereafter of me coming here, I again became 
chairman of the Department of City and Regional

40:42.696 --> 40:54.513
Planning. At this time it was a department. It was a 
department for a full year, and the dean made a

40:57.357 --> 41:06.670
decision that there would be no departments, that 
we would be called a program.

41:09.215 --> 41:15.268
So my business cards went from chairman to 
director. And there were directors of criminal

41:16.410 --> 41:21.621
justice, director of urban affairs, director of 
city and regional planning. That was, we had... We

41:28.537 --> 41:33.685
had a space on the second floor of University Hall 
that was just city and regional planning. We were

41:33.725 --> 41:37.530
not integrated with the Institute of Urban 
Studies on the fifth floor. We were separate and

41:37.790 --> 41:44.961
distinct from the very high visibility portion of 
the building where everyone could see us up at the

41:37.790 --> 41:44.961
stairwell.

41:47.585 --> 41:53.894
And we succeeded to gain in enrollments and we were 
doing just fine. The dean made a decision to

41:58.169 --> 42:26.185
integrate us fully with the institute of urban 
studies

41:58.169 --> 42:26.185
well you the dean had just asked you to take the job 
as chairman and you declined and i declined i had

